    <p class="text-black font-bold text-lg">Types of Commercial Properties</p><br>
    <p class="text-lg text-baits-gray">
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Office</span> is a commercial property that serves the sole purpose of using it as an office. Bulk of it is located in the Central Business District and co-developments on top of shopping malls. No forms of heavy storage is allowed in this type of property.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Retail</span> is a commercial property for retailers, fashion/F&B/etc. Located usually within shopping malls and ground level of neighbourhood areas, it enables by-passers to see the business product’s show-cases and entice them to walk in and enjoy the “user” experience provided by the owner/tenant.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Shophouse</span> is an interesting combination of commercial and residential property built mostly in the early 70s and 80s. This type of property is classified as a commercial property rather than a residential property in Singapore. This unique 2 storey property is a catchy to many retailers especially serving F&B.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Medical Suite</span> is a commercial property catering only to medical professions who holds a practising certification and license to operate.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Light Industrial</span> is a commercial property that allows business to carry out light industrial and manufacturing works within it.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Heavy Industrial</span> is a commercial property that allows business to carry out heavy industrial and manufacturing works within it.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Whole Building</span> is a commercial property and depending on the location it is built and the application applied and approved for, can be for Office and Light or Heavy Industrial works within it.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Buying Property</span> - Would-be owner(s) usually will engage a property agent to represent them when purchasing a property from the current owner of the property or the developer for new launches that protects their best interests in accordance with Singapore’s law.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Selling Property</span> - Owner(s) always have the lookout to engage a property agent to represent them when selling their property so that they would not be selling the property under value and protect their best interest in accordance with Singapore's law.
      <br><br>
      <span class="font-bold text-baits-blue">Renting Property</span> - Tenants will always engage a property agent to seek and source for property that meets their requirements and represent them to negotiate with the Owner. A Tenancy agreement handled by the property agent will uphold the agreed terms and conditions in accordance to Singapore’s law protecting both the tenant’s and owner’s interest.
